1
00:00:03,592 --> 00:00:17,149
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:19,753 --> 00:00:25,679
So this is November and it's time for our lugubrious contemplations.

3
00:00:26,161 --> 00:00:29,125
So we've done death, aging, sickness and all that.

4
00:00:29,484 --> 00:00:32,569
So now it comes to the contemplations of kamma.

5
00:00:33,223 --> 00:00:39,732
So first of all, in the Pali, karma, K-A-M-M-A, just means action.

6
00:00:40,514 --> 00:00:43,036
Consequences are called vipaka.

7
00:00:43,997 --> 00:00:51,307
And now, of course, our language uses the Sanskrit term karma with an R to mean consequence.

8
00:00:52,088 --> 00:00:57,796
So during this particular talk, when I talk about karma, I'm talking about the action.

9
00:00:59,244 --> 00:01:07,219
So the first little quote here is beings are owners of their actions, heirs of their actions.

10
00:01:07,960 --> 00:01:16,697
They originate from their actions, are bound to their actions, have their actions as their refuge.

11
00:01:16,677 --> 00:01:44,219
it is action that distinguishes beings from inferior and superior so this is not the distinguishment according to artistic or intellectual or physical talent this is to do with morals it's to do with whether we are moral or immoral virtuous um the equation is that the more deluded you are the more um

12
00:01:44,926 --> 00:01:49,632
unethical you will be, and the more wise you are, the more ethical.

13
00:01:51,073 --> 00:01:58,143
However, we'll be using this normal way of contemplating karma.

14
00:01:59,844 --> 00:02:01,486
I own my actions.

15
00:02:03,049 --> 00:02:05,572
I inherit the results of my actions.

16
00:02:07,433 --> 00:02:09,676
I am born of my actions.

17
00:02:11,179 --> 00:02:14,443
I form relations through my actions.

18
00:02:15,554 --> 00:02:18,377
I live dependent on my actions.

19
00:02:19,500 --> 00:02:31,717
And then a final catch-all phrase, whatever I do, for good or for ill, I shall inherit the results.

20
00:02:31,736 --> 00:02:38,727
Now, the first one, I own my actions.

21
00:02:42,688 --> 00:02:48,509
We are totally responsible for what we say, for what we think, and for what we do.

22
00:02:49,010 --> 00:02:50,034
It's coming out of us.

23
00:02:51,319 --> 00:02:53,728
That's the first thing to really grasp.

24
00:02:54,299 --> 00:03:00,770
And the consequences that come from that are dependent upon the intention.

25
00:03:01,491 --> 00:03:08,383
So remember, the role of intention in the Buddhist teachings is crucial and to be separated from desire.

26
00:03:09,004 --> 00:03:14,855
So there may be a desire to say something angry, but you see it and you let it go.

27
00:03:14,836 --> 00:03:19,201
But if you speak angrily, then that will have consequences.

28
00:03:19,481 --> 00:03:21,264
Remember, it goes into a matrix.

29
00:03:21,866 --> 00:03:35,824
The inner matrix of our psychology making us more angry and the outer matrix, which is all these people coming together to listen to what you said and you don't know what the response will be.

30
00:03:35,843 --> 00:03:43,694
You can't tell what the consequence of an action will be because it is either...

31
00:03:44,467 --> 00:03:54,967
enlarged or diminished by the milieu that it finds itself in, the environment that you speak into or do something into.

32
00:03:58,753 --> 00:04:04,485
So that's the reason that the Buddha constantly asks us to make wise reflections.

33
00:04:05,038 --> 00:04:08,304
and why we need a guide at this point.

34
00:04:08,424 --> 00:04:16,355
And I always think to myself how fortunate I am that I have such a wise person, the Buddha, to guide me.

35
00:04:17,937 --> 00:04:21,723
I doubt if there's anybody more wise than the Buddha.

36
00:04:21,862 --> 00:04:28,211
There may be somebody equal, but I doubt more wise, such is the profundity of his wisdom.

37
00:04:31,211 --> 00:04:32,774
So that's the important thing to understand.

38
00:04:33,516 --> 00:04:36,040
So something is a desire, nothing's happened.

39
00:04:36,541 --> 00:04:43,475
As soon as you empower that desire, if you remember the word chaitanya, the will, then something comes of it.

40
00:04:44,456 --> 00:04:49,446
And the general rule is that if something is good, some good will come of it.

41
00:04:49,586 --> 00:04:53,153
If something is not good, something not good will come of it.

42
00:04:55,175 --> 00:05:04,666
Now the second thing is, the second reflection is, I am heir to my kamma or I inherit the results of my kamma.

43
00:05:06,189 --> 00:05:11,235
So here we have to again remind ourselves of the specific law of conditionality.

44
00:05:11,956 --> 00:05:15,880
We don't know what will happen once we say something or do something.

45
00:05:16,461 --> 00:05:23,511
In fact, we don't know inwardly what will happen when we allow thoughts to develop within ourselves.

46
00:05:24,654 --> 00:05:37,935
So the important thing for me here is to accept what comes back to us, even though it's not directly related to my personal karma.

47
00:05:37,954 --> 00:05:44,565
Now, what that does away with, which I found a real freedom, a real liberation, is the need for punishment.

48
00:05:45,185 --> 00:05:47,490
Punishment comes on top of that.

49
00:05:47,790 --> 00:05:48,071
Right.

50
00:05:48,732 --> 00:05:56,942
So when we're self-criticizing, when we're full of aversive self-blaming, when we're beating ourselves up, it's all completely unnecessary.

51
00:05:57,423 --> 00:05:58,944
You do something unwholesome.

52
00:05:59,466 --> 00:06:00,627
It comes back to you.

53
00:06:00,648 --> 00:06:02,048
You bear the consequences.

54
00:06:02,350 --> 00:06:03,430
You learn from it.

55
00:06:04,132 --> 00:06:06,956
You make an intention not to do that again.

56
00:06:07,016 --> 00:06:08,737
And that's the end of it.

57
00:06:09,418 --> 00:06:09,798
Right.

58
00:06:09,819 --> 00:06:11,781
If you do it again, the same process.

59
00:06:11,961 --> 00:06:14,084
Habits are hard to overcome.

60
00:06:15,432 --> 00:06:29,372
If you do something that's really beautiful, something that's wonderful, and the response of praise comes towards you, you accept it, but there's no need to go into how wonderful I am, what an amazing person I really am.

61
00:06:30,052 --> 00:06:31,815
All that's not necessary.

62
00:06:33,478 --> 00:06:38,185
There's a little note here which concerns Hoddle.

63
00:06:38,625 --> 00:06:43,211
Now, Hoddle was the England manager between 96 and 99.

64
00:06:45,064 --> 00:06:52,632
And he somehow had this understanding, or at least this is what people thought was his understanding.

65
00:06:53,314 --> 00:07:01,963
Now, people who suffered some genetic disablement, that was the consequence of a past life.

66
00:07:03,105 --> 00:07:06,148
And it created such a furor, he had to resign.

67
00:07:07,088 --> 00:07:10,632
And according to the Buddha's teachings, that's not right.

68
00:07:10,747 --> 00:07:18,098
Because, of course, the body you receive is coming from all your past generations.

69
00:07:18,119 --> 00:07:24,850
What is your karma, no matter how unhappy you are with the body you've received?

70
00:07:24,870 --> 00:07:28,475
And it might not be that it's disabled.

71
00:07:29,076 --> 00:07:30,338
It might be that it's just ugly.

72
00:07:30,879 --> 00:07:31,740
You don't like it.

73
00:07:32,641 --> 00:07:37,870
Whatever the body you end up with is not the direct consequence.

74
00:07:37,951 --> 00:07:41,355
of your past actions, but the way you relate to it is.

75
00:07:45,199 --> 00:07:47,841
And then we have, I am born of my actions.

76
00:07:48,262 --> 00:07:51,367
So this is the understanding about habits, right?

77
00:07:51,406 --> 00:07:57,853
So remember that once you create a set of actions, you then develop a habit.

78
00:07:58,355 --> 00:08:05,663
And when we collect all our habits, that's our personality, that's our character, and it will drive us to our destiny.

79
00:08:05,980 --> 00:08:15,737
And our job is to see what is driving us to an unfortunate destiny, to perdition, and what is driving us towards a heavenly destiny.

80
00:08:17,894 --> 00:08:27,252
So this happens, of course, not only in terms of future lives, that's the normal understanding in Buddhism, that it does affect future life.

81
00:08:27,733 --> 00:08:34,907
In fact, your last consciousness as you die has a great effect on what's going to happen in the next life.

82
00:08:35,268 --> 00:08:38,113
It will drive you to do something about it.

83
00:08:39,427 --> 00:08:51,520
So if you die, for instance, with a lot of guilt on your mind, you did something which has just come up as you die and you die with that on your heart, in the next life, you want to do something about that.

84
00:08:52,602 --> 00:09:05,738
If your last thoughts are what a wonderful life you've had, what a wonderful relationship you had, then you'll be seeking the same thing in the next life.

85
00:09:11,422 --> 00:09:20,096
And remember that this also is happening in this present moment, and it's happening from day to day, from year to year.

86
00:09:20,856 --> 00:09:23,240
We're being reborn all the time.

87
00:09:23,442 --> 00:09:29,871
The only thing that happens at death is that the body falls off.

88
00:09:30,533 --> 00:09:34,779
And going back to the idea of genetic evolution,

89
00:09:35,182 --> 00:09:39,649
disease while I was at Amaravati Buddhist monastery.

90
00:09:39,688 --> 00:09:42,754
So this is going back, oh, 30 odd years now.

91
00:09:43,715 --> 00:09:51,486
There was a young man was brought to the monastery who was severely disabled from a genetic illness.

92
00:09:52,328 --> 00:10:00,260
And seemingly he was going to move into a flat and be quite fairly independent.

93
00:10:01,674 --> 00:10:06,400
And we were asked to, you know, go and have a chat with him and all that.

94
00:10:06,981 --> 00:10:10,426
And we would have to carry him to the toilet, things like that.

95
00:10:11,647 --> 00:10:14,990
And he was, you know, he was perfectly happy as far as we could see.

96
00:10:15,051 --> 00:10:22,080
He was accustomed to his situation and he'd adapted to it.

97
00:10:22,481 --> 00:10:33,735
So it seems that his parents have been told that such a thing could never happen again or it'd be a million in one chance of such a disease coming again.

98
00:10:34,115 --> 00:10:37,739
They had a daughter and the daughter suffered exactly the same.

99
00:10:39,041 --> 00:10:42,664
And seemingly she was extremely embittered.

100
00:10:42,684 --> 00:10:47,330
So here we have a similar situation and two different ways of coping with it.

101
00:10:49,293 --> 00:10:52,235
And that's the karma, the way they've coped with it.

102
00:10:54,712 --> 00:10:58,298
The next one is I form relations through my karma.

103
00:11:00,942 --> 00:11:19,269
So it can be sobering, really, to think about one's past relations, relationships that one has had, and just to see what we did, what we said, which either made them flower into something beautiful or disappear and crumble into something horrible.

104
00:11:20,363 --> 00:11:26,211
I mean, I personally have lots of regrets of being unkind and things like that.

105
00:11:27,052 --> 00:11:32,541
And it's sort of reflecting on that that makes you want to be different in the future.

106
00:11:36,567 --> 00:11:39,211
Now, here we have this interconnectedness.

107
00:11:39,230 --> 00:11:44,919
So here we're going back to this law, this specific law of conditionality.

108
00:11:45,067 --> 00:11:56,041
So it's the understanding that we are all interconnected, interdependent, that even these words, even these thoughts that I'm giving to you, they're not mine.

109
00:11:56,081 --> 00:11:57,243
They don't belong to me.

110
00:11:57,283 --> 00:11:58,565
I've read them all.

111
00:11:58,965 --> 00:12:04,312
In fact, I also use GPT to give me some ideas.

112
00:12:04,731 --> 00:12:12,881
And then I normally just fill out around those ideas and maybe add something that I picked up from somewhere else.

113
00:12:12,861 --> 00:12:18,707
So it's not as though anybody is completely original.

114
00:12:18,727 --> 00:12:20,450
I mean, that's very rare indeed.

115
00:12:20,490 --> 00:12:27,038
You'd have to be a Newton, an Einstein, you'd have to be an original musician, a composer, for instance.

116
00:12:27,758 --> 00:12:32,543
But all these people rest as, I think it was, was it Freud?

117
00:12:33,024 --> 00:12:36,607
Oh no, Jung, who sits on the shoulders of giants.

118
00:12:36,587 --> 00:12:39,956
So nothing is original, original, right?

119
00:12:40,057 --> 00:12:43,225
Everything has been either said before or done before.

120
00:12:45,210 --> 00:12:48,859
And we are this interconnectedness.

121
00:12:49,379 --> 00:13:00,535
We're not this, you know, it's very difficult for us Westerners to get away from the idea that we're little isolate modules, you know, whole entire.

122
00:13:00,576 --> 00:13:15,318
And that we somehow have this enormous little enormous wall around us to say, well, this is me and I'm not you, etc., etc.,

123
00:13:15,298 --> 00:13:37,880
and of course it it does it does affect the way we relate to people so um if i i mean the the philosophy that i always point to here is the south african philosophy of ubuntu which in short just says i am because we are right and it's just catching that

124
00:13:38,114 --> 00:13:59,750
relationship that we have and to realize that the relationships that we create with others affect the way they relate to us yeah and then there's i live dependent on my actions so this refers both to the inner and to the outer life

125
00:14:00,861 --> 00:14:07,309
And here we have, let's talk about a certain paradox, which is not understood in popular Buddhism.

126
00:14:08,071 --> 00:14:14,057
And that is that you can purposefully suffer and yet be inwardly perfectly happy.

127
00:14:16,900 --> 00:14:26,732
I once asked somebody in Sri Lanka, a born Buddhist, brought up as a Buddhist, why he thought Jesus Christ suffered such a terrible death.

128
00:14:26,753 --> 00:14:30,817
And he said, well, you know, he must have done something terrible in his past life.

129
00:14:32,822 --> 00:14:37,951
And that's the way, we might say, regular Buddhists, born Buddhists would think of that.

130
00:14:38,131 --> 00:14:43,461
Anything that happens to them, there must be some problem that is something they did in the past life.

131
00:14:44,623 --> 00:14:50,712
And so there's very little understanding that you can put yourself out for a cause, you know.

132
00:14:50,774 --> 00:14:56,383
You can become a martyr to a cause.

133
00:14:56,616 --> 00:15:04,467
So if we look at some, you know, our modern day saints and martyrs, I mean, the obvious ones that come up are Nelson Mandela.

134
00:15:05,067 --> 00:15:09,073
And for me, the very tragic figure of Alexei Navalny.

135
00:15:10,556 --> 00:15:16,344
And to lose someone, you know, with that clarity of vision and courage is really heart-rending.

136
00:15:16,423 --> 00:15:25,475
And especially when you hear that he would have been one of those released with the other people just recently.

137
00:15:28,678 --> 00:15:35,921
So I live dependent on my actions, right?

138
00:15:35,941 --> 00:15:38,388
And then we have this summary, which captures all.

139
00:15:38,870 --> 00:15:43,363
Whatever I do for good or for ill, I shall inherit the results.

140
00:15:45,283 --> 00:15:53,721
So now with these little contemplations, sorry, with these little reflections, we have to turn them into contemplations.

141
00:15:54,222 --> 00:15:59,073
And the way we do that is by repeating these phrases into the heart.

142
00:15:59,999 --> 00:16:03,243
And when you do that, you've got to be aware of any aversion.

143
00:16:03,423 --> 00:16:04,664
You don't want to know that.

144
00:16:04,684 --> 00:16:11,614
You don't want to feel what comes up when you say to yourself, I am heir to all my actions.

145
00:16:12,394 --> 00:16:18,602
And you have to keep repeating it and feeling that negativity if the negativity is there.

146
00:16:18,623 --> 00:16:25,331
And you have to wait until as the truth of that statement begins to penetrate

147
00:16:25,312 --> 00:16:27,322
that aversion begins to disappear.

148
00:16:27,764 --> 00:16:30,899
And finally, there's a feeling of digestion

149
00:16:31,927 --> 00:16:37,991
And when a contemplative subject is being digested, that's when it's going to change us.

150
00:16:38,011 --> 00:16:40,433
That's when it's changing our attitudes, right?

151
00:16:41,375 --> 00:16:42,495
So that's what we're going to do.

152
00:16:42,515 --> 00:16:47,860
We're going to spend a moment with each statement, a minute actually.

153
00:16:48,181 --> 00:16:50,283
I'm going to spend a minute with each statement.

154
00:16:51,104 --> 00:16:55,947
And during that time, if you just keep repeating it into the heart, right?

155
00:16:56,288 --> 00:16:58,309
So this is not an intellectual exercise.

156
00:16:58,809 --> 00:17:00,171
This is an emotional exercise.

157
00:17:00,192 --> 00:17:01,932
This is a heart exercise.

158
00:17:01,913 --> 00:17:05,720
And just keep repeating it gently to yourself.

159
00:17:05,740 --> 00:17:10,307
And then after the five minutes, we'll go into the sitting.

160
00:17:10,989 --> 00:17:13,192
And if you want to keep it up, yeah, that's fine.

161
00:17:13,854 --> 00:17:26,256
So what I'm going to now share with you is the page itself.

162
00:17:26,276 --> 00:17:26,757
Here we are.

163
00:17:31,714 --> 00:17:32,155
Okay.

164
00:17:33,636 --> 00:17:44,509
So I've highlighted those particular words, because they'll give you a clue as to what you have to remember.

165
00:17:45,371 --> 00:17:51,818
But I'll leave that on the screen for you.

166
00:17:52,199 --> 00:17:59,488
And if you want to just jot down those main words to remind yourself, and some of you will be able to take a screenshot.

167
00:18:00,970 --> 00:18:01,349
Okay.

168
00:18:04,469 --> 00:18:09,477
owner, inherit, born, relations, dependent.

169
00:18:11,200 --> 00:18:15,807
Whatever I do for good or for ill, I shall inherit the results.

170
00:18:20,015 --> 00:18:21,777
Okay.

171
00:18:21,798 --> 00:18:28,788
So if we go into a meditation, and I will

172
00:18:30,085 --> 00:18:34,971
Repeat those phrases and tie them to about a minute.

173
00:18:38,757 --> 00:18:41,121
Okay.

174
00:18:41,141 --> 00:18:41,942
So the first one.

175
00:18:43,644 --> 00:18:46,969
Again, remember repeating it into the heart.

176
00:18:48,510 --> 00:18:54,759
I am the owner of my actions of mind, speech and body.

177
00:19:58,477 --> 00:20:02,344
I inherit the results of my actions.

178
00:21:05,587 --> 00:21:12,155
I am born each moment, each day, each lifetime of my actions.

179
00:22:16,817 --> 00:22:20,752
I form relations through my actions.

180
00:23:23,051 --> 00:23:27,155
I live dependent on my actions.

181
00:24:30,383 --> 00:24:36,630
Whatever I do, for good or for ill, I shall inherit the results.

182
00:25:41,343 --> 00:25:48,990
Okay, so now we can either continue that contemplation or return to vipassana.

